SIMPLE: dodder
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dodder
<hw>Dod"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Dan.
<ets>dodder</ets>, Sw. <ets>dodra</ets>, G. <ets>dotter</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant of the genus <gen>Cuscuta</gen>. It is a
leafless parasitical vine with yellowish threadlike stems. It attaches
itself to some other plant, as to flax, goldenrod, etc., and decaying at
the root, is nourished by the plant that supports it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dodder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dodder
<hw>Dod"der</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS.
<ets>dyderian</ets> to deceive, delude, and E. <ets>didder</ets>,
<ets>dudder</ets>.]</ety> <def>To shake, tremble, or totter.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>doddering</xex> mast.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doddered</ent>⟦br⟧
